      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Question of Criteria For School Place of Honor</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Donald Nawi letter opposes posting of photo of Louis Farrakhan on principal's office wall at Nelson R Mandela Alternative High School in Mount Vernon, NY (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The walls of the principal's office of the 98 percent African-American Nelson R. Mandela Alternative High School in Mount Vernon, we are told in ''A School That's Theirs: 'It's Right in the Hood' '' (Sept. 3), are covered with posters of black leaders, including Malcolm X, Nelson Mandela and Louis Farrakhan.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The walls of the principal's office of the 98 percent African-American Nelson R. Mandela Alternative High School in Mount Vernon, we are told in ''A School That's Theirs: 'It's Right in the Hood' '' (Sept. 3), are covered with posters of black leaders, including Malcolm X, Nelson Mandela and Louis Farrakhan.</p>
        <p>Louis Farrakhan?</p>
        <p>I suppose if Mount Vernon had a 98 percent white alternative high school, the walls of the principal's office would include a picture of David Duke. Duke, after all, is a leader to some whites, and he would meet the only other apparent qualification to have one's poster hung in a one-race Mount Vernon alternative high school: his skin color.</p>
        <p>DONALD NAWI  New Rochelle</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
